ene", "prob": 0.997317910194397, "span": {"begin": 833, "end": 840}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:42758"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glucose", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9905164837837219, "span": {"begin": 864, "end": 871}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007333"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IR", "obj": "disease", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 888, "end": 890}}, {"id": ["mim:601665", "mesh:D009765"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "obesity", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999920129776001, "span": {"begin": 947, "end": 954}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003924", "mim:125853"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "type 2 diabetes mellitus", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999982714653015, "span": {"begin": 956, "end": 980}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008659"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "metabolic syndrome", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999950528144836, "span": {"begin": 982, "end": 1000}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002318"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cardiovascular disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999962449073792, "span": {"begin": 1002, "end": 1024}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005234"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "metabolism associated fatty liver disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9945665597915649, "span": {"begin": 1026, "end": 1067}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011085", "mim:184700"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "polycystic ovary syndrome", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999992251396179, "span": {"begin": 1072, "end": 1097}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008659"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "metabolic disorder", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999682307243347, "span": {"begin": 1115, "end": 1133}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3643"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1243, "end": 1245}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3630"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "insulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926711320877075, "span": {"begin": 1296, "end": 1303}}], "text": "Under normal physiological conditions, an increase in plasma glucose, for instance in the post-prandial phase, leads to increased insulin secretion by the pancreas, and consequent increase in plasma&nbsp;insulin concentration. The insulin increases glucose uptake into peripheral tissues, and inhibits hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis. In times of stress, the insulin response can be inhibited by stress hormones and proinhibitory cytokines, a mechanism known as insulin resistance (IR), that serves to maintain blood glucose levels during&nbsp;stress response (Tsatsoulis et al, 2013). Inappropriate stress hormone&nbsp;and cytokine generation can lead to individuals showing inappropriate insulin resistance, manifested as lack of&nbsp;insulin-stimulation of&nbsp;glucose uptake into adipose and muscle, and lack of&nbsp;insulin suppression of hepatic glucose release.&nbsp;  IR is associated with multiple health conditions including obesity, type 2 diabetes mellitus, metabolic syndrome, cardiovascular disease, metabolism associated fatty liver disease and polycystic ovary syndrome. It is a complex metabolic disorder, the exact causes of which are still to be fully resolved&nbsp;(Li et&nbsp;al, 2022). The mechanism by which IR manifests itself is primarily by abnormalities in insulin signal transduction (Pei et al, 2022).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:23:58 +0000 2026"}